{"cursor":"3517","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox nobility|type\n| name = Gjon Kastrioti II title = image = caption = alt = succession = CoA =\n| more = no reign = reign-type = predecessor = successor = suc-type = succession\n| = spouse = Irene Palaiologina spouse-type = Spouse issue = issue-link = issue-\n| pipe = full name = styles = titles = noble family = Kastrioti family house-\n| type = father = Skanderbeg mother = Donika Kastrioti birth_date = 1454\n| birth_place = christening_date = christening_place = death_date = 1514\n| death_place = burial_date = burial_place = occupation =\n}}\n\n'Gjon Kastrioti II' (ca. 1454 â 1514) was the son of Skanderbeg, the Albanian\nnational hero, and of Donika Kastrioti, daughter of Gjergj Arianit Komneni. He\nwas for a short time Lord of Kruja after his father death, Duke of San Pietro in\nGalatina (1485), Count of Soleto, Signore of Monte Sant'Angelo and San Giovanni\nRotondo. In 1495 Ferdinand I of Naples gave the title of the Signore of Gagliano\ndel Capo and Oria. While in his teens he was forced to leave the country after\nthe death of his father in 1468. He is known also for his role in the Albanian\nuprising of 1481, when after reaching the Albanian coast from Italy, he tried to\nstruggle against the Ottomans. Unsuccessful,\nhe retired in Italy in 1484. In June 1481 he\nsupported forces of Ivan CrnojeviÄ to recapture Zeta from Ottomans.\n\nHe married Irene Palaiologina, daughter of despot Lazar BrankoviÄ of Serbia and\ngreat-granddaughter of the Byzantine emperor Manuel II Palaiologos. The\nCastriota Scanderbeg living in Italy today represent the only descendants of\nManuel II Palaiologos.\n","linknr":128,"url":"Gjon_Kastrioti_II","recorded":1375056180,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Gjon_Kastrioti_II&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Gjon_Kastrioti_II&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommon